Movie: The Hunger Games: The Ballad of Songbirds & Snakes

Review: Honestly way better than I remembered. Cool when a YA blockbuster book/movie has sharp commentary and a lot going on. While the movie sometimes lacks in fleshing out Katniss's key relationships with Cinna and even Peeta, her arc is nonetheless strong and compelling. Instead or rushing into the games and the Peeta/Gale drama, actual time and patience are taken to allow us to see her growth from quiet unknown into defiant, self-defined underdog. Review: Far and away the best of the three, so I'm willing to forgive the 30 minutes of epilogue. Totally unashamed campiness and dazzling cinematography (the smeagol/gollum reflection scene alone is a masterclass) make Return of the King a wholly immersive and thrilling viewing experience like few others.

The Lord of the Rings: The Fellowship of the Ring

Review: Definitely a significant step down from the first one. Pays too much attention to the other movies and larger story instead of *this* story, whereas this was an area where the original excelled and that really contributed to its success (as I noted in my original review: letterboxd.com/zackhersh/film/the-hunger-games/ )

I'm usually a sucker for adventure movies but this was surprisingly brutal. After we're through the exposition it's a nonstop trip and does get into a nice roll of action adventure sequences, especially once the titular "tomb raiding" actually goes down — just wish that started way sooner, and that there was more of it and less people shooting each other!
Magical and amazing 😍😍 Especially before Ponyo starts talking! If only the whole movie were like that
